If you want to see an end to the gender pay gap vote for a Labour government for the many not the few (8/8)

Following the footsteps of Barbara Castle a Labour government will close this gap through a ¬£10 an hour real living wage fining organisations that fail to reduce their pay gaps sectoral collective bargaining and ending the public sector pay gap (7/8)

But while we might have won the battle on the legal principle of equal pay we haven‚Äôt on the gender pay gap Since women are all too often concentrated in sectors and industries with low pay there is still a gender pay gap of 13.1 for full-time workers (6/8)
Barbara Castle‚Äôs Equal Pay Act made it illegal for the first time to pay men and women different rates for the same work It was a huge milestone (5/8)

When Dagenham‚Äôs women machinists went on strike in protest at being paid lower rates than their male colleagues Castle defied convention and met them in her office for tea to listen to their concerns She then campaigned for legislation to tackle unequal pay (4/8)

Castle acknowledged that equal pay was fundamentally a left-wing issue ‚ÄòThere has been equal pay for some time for clever articulate professional women, she said ‚ÄòToday we are talking about poor women. (3/8)

Labour is the only party that has truly adopted a policy of ‚Äòdeeds not words on equal pay Next year marks the 50th anniversary of the Equal Pay Act championed by Barbara Castle a Labour icon and a pioneering woman MP (2/8)

Today is Equal Pay Day the day in the year where women effectively stop getting paid relative to their male counterparts That is why Labour‚Äôs announcement that we will close the gender pay gap by 2030 is such a vital and important one (1/8
